         <head>NOTES <hi rend="small">TO THE </hi>POEM <hi rend="small">OF </hi>
                        MICHAEL.</head>
         <div xml:id="note1m">
            <head>
               <hi rend="small">NOTE I. </hi>
            </head>
            <p rend="note">Page 213—line 14 “There’s Richard
                            Bateman,” &amp;c. The story alluded to here is well known in the
                            country. The chapel is called Ings Chapel; and is on the right hand side
                            of the road leading from Kendal to Ambleside.</p>
         </div>
         <div xml:id="note2m">
            <head>
               <hi rend="small">NOTE II. </hi>
            </head>
            <p rend="note">Page 217—line 4 “———had
                            design’d to build a sheep-fold.” &amp;c. It may be proper to
                            inform some readers, that a sheep-fold in these mountains is an unroofed
                            building of stone walls, with different divisions. It is generally
                            placed by the side of a brook, for the convenience of washing the sheep;
                            but it is also useful as a shelter for them, and as a place to drive
                            them into, to enable the shepherds conveniently to single out one or
                            more for any particular purpose.</p>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <closer>
               <hi rend="bold">
                  <emph>FINIS</emph>. </hi>
            </closer>
         </div>
